Security Issues
 Project Security
User privacy
•	Risk(high): User data such as log in information and card scans will be stored using Supabase. This information contains sensitive information that could jeopardize the privacy of users if not securely stored.
•	Prevention: We’ve put trust in the authentication, and secure storage practices of the host database Supabase and their Cloud storage solution.
Possible Attack Vectors & Mitigations
XSS (cross-site scripting)
•	Mitigation: Escape/encode all user-generated content displayed in the UI; use frameworks’ safe templating; set CSP headers.
CSRF (cross-site request forgery)
•	Mitigation: Use CSRF tokens for state-changing endpoints, or rely on same-site cookies and JWT in the Authorization header.
SQL injection
•	Mitigation: Use parameterized queries. Avoid building SQL by concatenation.
Insecure file uploads (malicious content, huge files)
•	Mitigation: Check file signatures, set size limits, generate secure signed URLs for access. Strip EXIF metadata if privacy-sensitive.
SSRF (server side request forgery) via URLs in uploaded metadata or external API calls
•	Mitigation: Validate/whitelist domains, restrict outgoing network egress from backend containers, use DNS controls and HTTP timeouts.
Privilege escalation / exposed admin endpoints
•	Mitigation: Protect admin APIs with additional auth layers; log all admin actions.
Secrets leakage in images or builds
•	Mitigation: Build images in CI with secrets injected at runtime, scan images for secrets, use small base images and non-root containers.
Dependency / supply chain attacks
•	Mitigation: Pin dependency versions, use SCA (software composition analysis) tools, regularly run vulnerability scans (e.g., Dependabot, Snyk), review install scripts.
Model adversarial attacks & data poisoning
•	Mitigation: Do not auto-train on user-submitted content without vetting, keep an isolated training pipeline, and test model robustness. Monitor for anomalous query patterns and rate-limit to prevent extraction.


